                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d281">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.022/6–1153</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum of Conversation, by the Deputy Legal Adviser
                        (Tate)</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian"
                            type="conversation-or-meeting-date" when="1953-06-11">June 11,
                            1953</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <item>Subject:</item>
                    <item>Continental Shelf Bill <gloss target="#t_S1">S.</gloss> 1901</item>
                </list>
                <p>Senator Cordon called me this afternoon and asked me if, from the international
                    viewpoint, it would be permissible to extend the Constitution and laws of the
                    United States to the seabed and subsoil of the continental shelf if the bill
                    made it clear that there was no attempt to extend the applicability of United
                    States law to the super-adjacent waters and air. I told him that it would be
                    permissible to do so.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Jack B. Tate</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
